{"author":{"id":"ebf67eb466641f17fe66357119d643fd1930eee58a1f1e4b000ea473bf729ed1"},"ops":[{"type":6,"timestamp":1745389174,"nonce":"Lcrmfb5Q4SK75thXZshIu60MooU=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lAHOAW4Y0s6zlAZgzniMEa0"},"target":"efa9788c815fa1a3208d7577cc50368c287780143651498bb36a6211211ebbe0","message":"Hi, \n\nIt seems PhyLM has an issue with Sequential option in \"Changes interleaved format\". The default value is Interleaved, and with the default option PhyLM works on both interleaved and sequential types of phylip format. With Sequential option PhyML jobs run forever, even on a small dataset. The test data is \"sequential\" version of phylip.\nhttps://usegalaxy.eu/u/igor/h/phyml\nDataset 1 is the test file from github; 2-4 completed PhyML job with the default settings; 5-7 - job with \"sequential\" option. \n\nI have impression \"Changes interleaved format\" is redundant. With the default setting (Interleaved) PhyML handles both interleaved and sequential types of phylip format and produce identical tree formulas. In the history datasets ##8 and 9 contain an alignment (from Wiki) in sequential and interleaved phylip formats. The tree formulas are concatenated in dataset 16. The results look identical to me. \n\nThe issue is long (infinite?) run time with Sequential option. If PhyML handle both types of data correctly, does it need \"Changes interleaved format\"? \n\nThank you!\nIgor","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1745389192,"nonce":"hQKZkS/Fv/QYVage+1CSGel/M+8=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lAHOAW4Y0s6zlAZgzniMEzM"},"target":"efa9788c815fa1a3208d7577cc50368c287780143651498bb36a6211211ebbe0","message":"Hi, \n\nIt seems PhyLM has an issue with Sequential option in \"Changes interleaved format\". The default value is Interleaved, and with the default option PhyLM works on both interleaved and sequential types of phylip format. With Sequential option PhyML jobs run forever, even on a small dataset. The test data is \"sequential\" version of phylip.\nhttps://usegalaxy.eu/u/igor/h/phyml\nDataset 1 is the test file from github; 2-4 completed PhyML job with the default settings; 5-7 - job with \"sequential\" option. \n\nI have impression \"Changes interleaved format\" is redundant. With the default setting (Interleaved) PhyML handles both interleaved and sequential types of phylip format and produce identical tree formulas. In the history datasets 8 and 9 contain an alignment (from Wiki) in sequential and interleaved phylip formats. The tree formulas are concatenated in dataset 16. The results look identical to me. \n\nThe issue is long (infinite?) run time with Sequential option. If PhyML handle both types of data correctly, does it need \"Changes interleaved format\"? \n\nThank you!\nIgor","files":null}]}